50	TaskListing model	<p>Our stack with React/Redux/Next/Graphql/Django/Postgresql is working well, but with our normalised data model it could be said to be "optimised for writes" and with graphql being used we are seeing 1.5s on high spec laptops and 5.5s on Heroku for database queries related to loading lists of &lt; 100 tasks as requested by graphene/graphql etc.</p>\n<p>Given we have already tried the easy option of optimising graphene with a libarary (https://github.com/tfoxy/graphene-django-optimizer I believe), I propose that rather than needing to query an expanding graph of objects/tables to load tasks in a list, that we create a TaskListing model that stores everything required to display a "Task Listing" in one model / database table. This is read-optimised and means that displaying the list of tasks on the homepage or on the Tasks  of a Product, will require querying a single table backing the TaskListing model - and this will be super simple and super fast.</p>\n<p>This is a kind of proactive backend caching / denormalisation, however we are managing it ourselves explicitly and doing so as a first-class django model: TaskListing. Later,  TaskListing  also be stored in Redis or elastic or something else fast/in-memory, but for now our goal is to make things run super fast (as in &lt;100ms to return thousands of tasks from the database) with the stack we have,  adding other tech into the stack. So please do not add anything other than the TaskListing model and let's get this super fast using postgresql and the rest of our current stack.</p>\n<p>You could think of this TaskListing model as a kind of "advertisement" for the Task with all the info required, once you want to do something beyond reading the advertisement you cross over into real models. The TaskListing model will effectively store a copy of all the data that is required for the lists of tasks (all Task, TaskClaim, depedencies etc. data) so that then whenever you list Tasks, you actually list TaskListings.</p>\n<p>It should be possible to completely regenerate TaskListings from the database, and also whenever a related object is updated (or if a task is removed) it should update the related TaskListing. So any updates to any relevant source model attributes should update the related TaskListing... when you click on a TaskListing to view the detail, you are then viewing the Task and related models.</p>\n<p>The relationship I think that makes sense is that TaskListing has a reference to both the Product and Task - with product_id and task_id being both indexed in TaskListing's table. That is: Product has many TaskListings, Task has one TaskListing. This way the database query to list tasks is super simple and fast - you just list all the TaskListings on the homepage, and for a product it's filtered to the TaskListings for that product.</p>\n<p>When you click on a TaskListing, you then view the Task detail view as is currently the case That is, no other functionality needs to change - we are just creating a consolidated model that acts as the "advertisement" version of a Task with all the content required when listing a set of tasks in one place.</p>\n	Create a model that has all the content in a single place for fast loading of listings of Tasks	4	{}	f	f	0	18	t	{"username": "adrian", "full_name": "Adrian McPhee"}	{"username": "adrian", "full_name": "Adrian McPhee"}	{"username": "adrian", "full_name": "Adrian McPhee"}	3	{"id": 21, "kind": 0, "task": 100, "person": 8}	{"username": "nazar", "full_name": "Nazar Revutsky"}	f	\N	\N	100	8d5c116e-fbdd-4065-af07-e08abca21563	{"name": "ou Product Factory", "slug": "ou-product-factory", "owner": "meta", "website": "https://ou.com", "video_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OWXVryhdoVA", "detail_url": null}	d3d50522-9132-4c5a-b72e-9a36314cc823	\N	\N	t	\N
